{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631814"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17399"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17399"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.64,0,0.11,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70425"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55889"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6665"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70425"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal carotid artery is a major vessel supplying blood to the brain and eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Through which one of the following sites does it enter the skull?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen ovale","Carotid canal","Foramen spinosum","Foramen magnum","Jugular foramen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal carotid artery enters the skull through the carotid canal\u003C/strong\u003E in the petrous part of the temporal bone. After entering the skull, it travels through the cavernous sinus before giving off its terminal branches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForamen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E - This transmits the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (V3)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForamen spinosum\u003C/strong\u003E - This transmits the middle meningeal artery and meningeal branch of mandibular nerve\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForamen magnum\u003C/strong\u003E - This transmits the vertebral arteries, spinal cord, medulla oblongata and accessory nerves\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJugular foramen\u003C/strong\u003E - This transmits the internal jugular vein and cranial nerves IX, X, and XI\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe internal carotid artery provides the main blood supply to the anterior circulation of the brain via its terminal branches: the anterior and middle cerebral arteries. It also gives rise to the ophthalmic artery, which supplies the eye and orbital contents.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The internal carotid artery enters the skull through the carotid canal in the petrous temporal bone.","The internal carotid artery gives rise to the ophthalmic, posterior communicating, anterior cerebral, and middle cerebral arteries.","The internal carotid artery has four segments: cervical, petrous, cavernous, and cerebral."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake RL (Richard L, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM. Gray\u2019s Anatomy for Students. Fifth edition. Elsevier; 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55889"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17399"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55889"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T09:09:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T09:10:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10089"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70425"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0"